<ab><lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Πάμφιλος">Π<unclear reason="damage">αμ</unclear>φίλου</name>  <space extent="3" unit="character"/> <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Μιθροδάτης">Μιθροδάτου</name></persName></persName> <space extent="1" unit="character"/>  <orig n="unresolved">με</orig><gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/>  <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Ἀρκαθίας">Ἀ<unclear reason="damage">ρ</unclear>καθίου</name> <space extent="3" unit="character"/> <w lemma="ὁ">τοῦ</w> <name nymRef="#Μιθροδάτης">Μιθροδάτου</name></persName> <orig n="unresolved"><unclear reason="damage">ε</unclear></orig><gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/><lb n="3"/> <w>ἀρχιπερσου</w> <orig n="unresolved">του</orig> <space extent="3" unit="character"/>  </ab>
</div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>Of Pamphilos (son) of Mithrodates Me[-] [...] of Arkathios son of Mithrodates E[-] [...] archiperses. </p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>There is no immediate explanation for the use of the genitive case for the main figure(s) - Pamphilos apparently, and, if we have two - or even three? - columns, Mithrodates. Could Ἀρχιπερσης (? Ἀρχιπερσους) be a name? If this is a title it seems to imply the presence of a group claiming to be survivals of the Persian occupation - or ?? of a group involved in a Persian (or allegedly Persian) cult. If this were Mithraism it would - at the probable date - be of considerable importance.</p>
            <p>See P. Briant, DHA 11 (1985) 167-95 on Persia in Asia Minor SEG 35.1080.</p>
            <p>L. Carie 77: Persian names at Tabae, Sebastopolis and Heraclea suggest Persian colonies.</p>
            <p>L. Robert, on Iranians in Asia Minor, BCH 107 (1983) 505-9</p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography" n="none">
            <p>Unpublished.</p>
         </div>
